The article discusses the challenges faced by American families during the COVID-19 pandemic and the economic crisis. It emphasizes the need to protect consumers from fraud and privacy invasions in the digital marketplace. Scammers have taken advantage of the pandemic by creating fake websites and advertisements for personal protective equipment and exploiting stimulus payments. The Biden administration is committed to combating these criminals and ensuring that companies providing digital services prioritize consumer privacy and data protection. The administration also recognizes the importance of educating consumers to make informed choices online and protect themselves from fraudulent schemes. Additionally, efforts are being made to prevent abuses that could lead to individuals and families losing their homes. The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau offers resources for homeowners and renters to learn about relief programs and resources. The Federal Trade Commission and the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, along with law enforcement agencies, work to fight predatory practices and privacy violations. National Consumer Protection Week aims to educate and protect the American people from marketplace threats. President Biden proclaims February 28 to March 6, 2021, as National Consumer Protection Week and calls upon government officials, industry leaders, and advocates to share information about consumer protection and citizens' rights.